subject: [off topic] Help please.
msgSnippet: Hello everyone, this is my first post to this list though I have been reading its messages for long. First of all, congratulations for this wonderfull mail
messageBody:
Hello everyone,

this is my first post to this list though I have been reading its messages for long.

First of all, congratulations for this wonderfull mail list and thank you very much for reading this message.

I apologise for the topic of my horrible English and for the topic of my question, which has nothing to do with JUnit; it is about obfuscating the source code.

The company I work for is about to release a Java API, so we want to protect ourselves against dishonest customers that may want to decompile the binaries (jar files). This is why we are looking for a good obfuscator. I have no experience with obfuscators but my boss has ordered me to get a good one, no matter whether it is commercial or not.

Please let me know what obfuscators you use and what about the experience with them.

I look forward to hearing from you.




> -----Mensaje original-----
> De: Chad Woolley [SMTP:lists@...]
> Enviado el: martes, 11 de noviembre de 2003 10:57
> Para: junit@yahoogroups.com
> Asunto: Re: [junit] Digest Number 1040
>
> Nathan Coast wrote:
> > Hi,
> >
> > Is anyone doing performance testing with junit or a junit extension? I've
> > looked at JUnitPerf and I don't think it has the functionality I need. I'd like
> > to record the time taken to execute individual junit tests. The idea is that it
> > should then be possible identify when code changes occurred that caused a
> > significant drop in performance.
> >
> > thanks
> > Nathan
>
> You could probably do this if you wrote a custom TestRunner.
>
> If you know Aspect-Oriented Programming, this also seems like a good use for it.
> It would be fairly simple to write an aspect which reported elapsed execution
> time on a per-test-method level. You could write the data on all tests for each
> run to a CSV file, for example. Then you could use a spreadsheet or other tool
> to perform trend analysis on the collected data over time.
>
>
